>Now in txt2img" and "img2img", you have a new function called additional networks, open it up, Click Enable. And select Your "model1" as the newly acquired Lora files.

>I REFUSE TO PARTICIPATE IN A LITERAL BLOODBATH!

No one but you has said anything about a "literal blood bath".

The term "washed in the blood of the Lamb" is a symbolic term referring to Christ's death on the cross, meaning that Christ's death on the cross an the shedding of His blood cleanses us from sin if we accept Him as the Messiah, Savior, and Redeemer. All we have to do is ask for forgiveness of our sins, and God, in the name of Jesus, will forgive us of our sins.

The sacrifice of lambs, turtle doves, calves, etc., symbolized and pointed forward to the Messiah who would become the ultimate sacrifice for the remission of everyone's sins.

When Christ died on the cross, the curtain in the temple between the Holy Place and the Most Holy Place (where God's presence was manifested) was torn in two from top to bottom by God, and the sacrifices ceased, because the supreme sacrifice to which they pointed had been made. There was no more need to shed blood to get forgiveness of sin.

The only bath that we are instructed to take is the "bath" of baptism--being submerged then raised up out of water--as a demonstration of our acceptance of Christ as our Lord and Savior. No blood is involved, because the Messiah, Jesus Christ, paid the price of sin with His blood, once and for all.

>I hate the idea of god the father being the merciless abuser that god the son willingly submitted to out of love. It’s like god is love and hate at the same time.

God did not punish His son. Adam and Eve sinned by intentionally disobeying God, separating them and all mankind (all of their descendants) from God. Sin is willful disobedience of God's will. God's will--his law. The wages of sin is death. Instead of destroying Adam and Eve and their descendants, the human race, God the Father, the Holy Spirit, and His Son devised the plan of salvation: The Son willingly came to this earth, being incarnated as a human being, lived a sinless life, and was crucified to atone for the sins of every person who had lived and who would live until His return. His resurrection from the dead at the dawning of the third day after his crucifixion showed that His sacrifice--his atonement for our sins--was sufficient to cover all of our sins. He died the death of condemnation that we should have died, in our place, so that we do not have to if we accept Him as our Lord and Savior and live our lives in accordance with His will, and ask forgiveness of our sins whenever we fall short and, in our weakness, yield to sin.

The Messiah's (Jesus') WILLING sacrifice for our sins is not merciless at all. It is the ultimate act of mercy, forgiveness and love. God didn't commit a merciless act by punishing His Son. Instead, God committed the ultimate act of love for mankind by ALLOWING His Son, Jesus Christ, to sacrifice Himself to overcome sin and evil so that we might have eternal life at the resurrection, when all of the dead who have followed God the Father and Christ the Son will be resurrected in perfect bodies, and Satan and sin will be destroyed forever.

>Brothers in Christ are you American or are you a son of the most high?

Render unto Caesar (the government) the things that are Caesar's, and unto God the things that are Gods. We are to obey the laws of the land as long as those laws do not violate God's laws; and we are to obey God's laws above all.

Obedience to God's law comes first and foremost. Obedience to the nation's laws comes second.

In the United States of America, the laws of the land as outlined in the Constitution of the United States, reflect the laws of God for the most part.

We are to love God with all our heart, soul, and mind; and we are to love others as we love ourselves.

All of the federal laws of the United States are based on those two principles. Any laws that are enacted that disagree with God's laws are to be disregarded.

The Ten Commandments are divided into those two categories: our obligation to God, as given in the first 4 commandments; and our obligation to our fellow human beings as given in the last 6 commandments.

Again, adherence to God's law comes first. Adherence to the nation's laws that are in harmony with God's law comes second.

Laws like tax laws, that seem to be grey areas are to be weighed by asking ourselves, "Does it go against God's law?" Tax laws, for example, do not violate God's law, so they are valid laws, and are to be honored and obeyed.
